sec.p:
Nursing research courses are introduced at the undergraduate level in nearly every baccalaureate nursing program at the national, regional and international levels. The National League for Nurses has recommended that all baccalaureate programs include research content in their curriculum (NLN, 1992). This includes nursing practice, nursing education and nursing administration. There have been international studies in Europe and the United States that addressed nursing research from different perspectives. Some of these studies examined the students’ attitudes towards nursing research (Padilla and de Carvalho, 1993; Morse et al., 1996; Kajermo et al., 2000; Bjorkstrom et al., 2003). However, the Jordanian literature has a dearth of studies that address research practice and utilisation. To our knowledge, no previous study in Jordan addresses attitudes of Jordanian nursing students towards nursing research. This study was conducted to fill that gap and to add to our knowledge and information about nursing education needs in relation to nursing research. This is particularly important at a time where efforts are being made through the recently established Jordanian Nursing Council (2008) to raise the standards of nursing practice and education in Jordan. The information from the study also contributes to the international agenda for promoting nursing research. Thus, the purpose of this study was to investigate the attitudes of Jordanian nursing students towards the conduct and utilisation of nursing research. The specific aims were to:


explore the attitudes of the Jordanian nursing students towards the conduct and utilisation of nursing research;

examine differences in attitudes of nursing students towards the conduct and utilisation of nursing research in relation to selected demographic and personal characteristics.
